"Evans N., Baierl A., Semenov M.A., Gladders P., Fitt B.D.L.","Range and severity of a plant disease increased by global warming",2008,"Journal of the Royal Society Interface","5","22",,"525","531",,,10.1098/rsif.2007.1136,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-40749129355&partnerID=40&md5=3a12656f86dbeac4e7aa3e67c9a8bcf6","Rothamsted Research, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom; Department of Statistics and Decision Support Systems, University of Vienna, Universitaetsstrasse 5/9, 1010 Vienna, Austria; ADAS Boxworth, Battlegate Road, Boxworth, Cambridge CB3 8NN, United Kingdom","Evans, N., Rothamsted Research, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom; Baierl, A., Rothamsted Research, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom, Department of Statistics and Decision Support Systems, University of Vienna, Universitaetsstrasse 5/9, 1010 Vienna, Austria; Semenov, M.A., Rothamsted Research, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom; Gladders, P., ADAS Boxworth, Battlegate Road, Boxworth, Cambridge CB3 8NN, United Kingdom; Fitt, B.D.L., Rothamsted Research, Harpenden, Hertfordshire AL5 2JQ, United Kingdom","Climate change affects plants in natural and agricultural ecosystems throughout the world but little work has been done on the effects of climate change on plant disease epidemics. To illustrate such effects, a weather-based disease forecasting model was combined with a climate change model predicting UK temperature and rainfall under high- and low-carbon emissions for the 2020s and 2050s. Multi-site data collected over a 15-year period were used to develop and validate a weather-based model forecasting severity of phoma stem canker epidemics on oilseed rape across the UK. This was combined with climate change scenarios to predict that epidemics will not only increase in severity but also spread northwards by the 2020s. These results provide a stimulus to develop models to predict the effects of climate change on other plant diseases, especially in delicately balanced agricultural or natural ecosystems. Such predictions can be used to guide policy and practice in adapting to effects of climate change on food security and wildlife. © 2007 The Royal Society.","Climate change scenarios; Leptosphaeria maculans; Phoma stem canker; Plant disease epidemiology; Weather-based disease forecasts","Diseases; Epidemiology; Mathematical models; Plants (botany); Climate change scenarios; Leptosphaeria maculans; Phoma stem canker; Plant disease epidemiology; Weather-based disease forecasts; Climate change; article; ascospore; climate change; disease severity; ecosystem; food security; greenhouse effect; plant disease; stem canker; temperature sensitivity; weathering; Ascomycota; Brassica rapa; Disease Outbreaks; Great Britain; Greenhouse Effect; Host-Pathogen Interactions; Models, Biological; Plant Diseases; Reproducibility of Results; Time Factors; Brassica napus; Leptosphaeria maculans; Phoma",,,,,,"Anderson, P.K., Cunningham, A.A., Patel, N.G., Morales, F.J., Epstein, P.R., Daszak, P., Emerging infectious diseases of plants: Pathogen, pollution, climate change and agrotechnology drivers (2004) Trends Ecol. Evol, 19, pp. 535-544. , doi:10.1016/j.tree.2004.07.021; GENSTAT release 9 reference manual (2006) Release 9 reference manual, , Oxford, UK: VSN International. Anon; Bearchell, S.J., Fraaije, B.A., Shaw, M.W., Fitt, B.D.L., Wheat archive links long-term fungal pathogen population dynamics to air pollution (2005) Proc. Natl Acad. Sci. USA, 102, pp. 5438-5442. , doi:10.1073/pnas.0501596102; Bergot, M., Cloppet, E., Pérarnaud, V., Déqué, M., Marçais, B., Desprez-Loustau, M.-L., Simulation of potential range expansion of oak disease caused by Phytophthora cinnamomi under climate change (2004) Global Change Biol, 10, pp. 1539-1552. , doi:10.1111/j.1365- 2486.2004.00824.x; Bosch, J., Carrascal, L.M., Duran, L., Walker, S., Fisher, M.C., Climate change and outbreaks of amphibian chytridiomycosis in a 